  "prompt": "U.S. Immigration: Can an H1-B visa be extended by future employers beyond 6 years based on an approved I-140 through the previous employer?",
  "response": "Yes, an H-1B visa can be extended beyond the standard 6-year maximum duration if certain conditions are met, particularly in relation to an approved I-140 petition.\n\nIf you have an approved I-140 (Immigrant Petition for Alien Worker) through a previous employer and are in the process of obtaining a green card, you may be eligible for H-1B extensions beyond the 6 years. The key conditions for this extension include:\n\n1. **Pending Labor Certification or I-140 Petition**: If your I-140 has been approved but you cannot adjust your status to a green card because your priority date is not current, you can typically apply for H-1B extensions in 1-year increments.\n\n2. **Approved I-140 with New Employer**: If you switch employers, the new employer can file for an H-1B petition on your behalf. If you have an approved I-140 that is not revoked and you fulfill the other requirements, you can still qualify for extensions beyond the typical 6 years with the new H-1B petition.\n\n3. **Other Considerations**: Be sure that the new employer's I-140 petition is properly filed and that your case meets other criteria established by U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS).\n\nIt's advisable to consult with an immigration attorney to understand the specific circumstances and to navigate the application and extension processes properly, as individual cases can vary greatly based on the details of the situation.",
